(2, 'My First Semester - Tate Mclean', '<p><strong>First day</strong></p><p>The first day at university was myself walking to there using the interactive map on the UoN website, which was very hard to use while being on a phone. But I gave myself plenty of time to get there, so I didn’t come late to my first lecture.</p><p>My first lecture was INFT1004, within the Great hall at Callaghan. I attempted to make friends at first, and me a person who was friendly, the lecture wasn’t anything special, it was just an introduction like most first year lecture, and the person I met fell asleep next to me, so that was a bit funny. The lecturer recommended to download lost on campus app. Which I did ASAP. I only have one lecture on my first day.</p><p><strong>Semester Bulk</strong></p><p>After that, I came back for the rest of the week and basically just kept to myself, I attended each lecture and workshop following on that, to keep up to date with all of the content that was being offered.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The first semester that I had was nothing special, I followed on with each piece of content and assessment somewhat easily, as going to each class really helped out with the hardest parts of the assessments that I was being given.</p><p>I didn’t go to one workshop and I was lost on what to do, the lectures did always say if you have any problems around the assessments, you should email them, which I did, and they put me on track.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Always kept ample room to get assessments complete on time, and if I had any problems I would either bring my laptop into workshops to get help, or I would email. Some assessments were very stressful and I felt very clueless on how to do a couple things, and what path I should take with an assessment, but going to the teachers for all of this information was the correct thing to do.</p><p><strong>Exams</strong></p><p>Studying for exams was probably the most stressful thing I’ve ever done, you will tend to second guess yourself on if you know every part of information, but you have to remember that you are human, and you can’t remember everything, luckily as an IT student reference sheets were used.</p><p>The exam days were the most anxious thing I had done back then, as reference sheets were in nearly all of my courses, even through lectures said ‘you can’t put the whole semester on your paper’. Even through I nearly did put the whole semester on it. It really helped as nearly every question that I was stuck on, I would have to dive into my reference sheet to find the answer. It was not very time efficient what so ever, but it worked. I do not advise this at all!!</p>', 'tate', '2021-05-29 02:54:07', '2021-05-29 02:54:07'),
(3, 'My first semester - Quenton', '<p><strong>My first day</strong></p><p>Like most first year students, I was nervous when I first went to university. In case I could not find my way on the first day of class, I spent a day in advance acquainting myself with the campus. When I walked around campus, I used an app called ‘Lost on Campus’ which was recommended by my roommate. This app shows a route between the user and the destination in the campus. I thought this app was not that useful, the map was not detailed enough and there were sometimes delays. I found there were general maps printed in many parts of the campus, so I used my phone to take a photo of it. That became my main method to find my route in my future time.</p><p><strong>My first class</strong></p><p>My first class is a lecture. Thanks to my familiarity with the campus in advance, I get to the classroom easily. It was a great Amphitheatre. All students who enrolled in the same course that semester listened to the teacher explain the course content. A course usually consists of two parts, one is lecture and the other is workshop. Workshop is sometimes called lab; it is like students who enroll in the course are divided into several groups and do some tasks. One or two tutors help students solve the problems they encounter. My first week there were no workshops.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Most of the semester time</strong></p><p>After lectures and workshops, I usually go to the library. The library is a good place for study, it has a good stock of books which may help with the study. Besides, it is a place with a good learning atmosphere. I usually meet some other students who are doing the same courses. We solved some issues by studying together. Also, it is a nice opportunity to make friends there.</p><p><strong>Assessment</strong></p><p>In general, each course has its assessment which may contain essays, assignments, projects and exams. Usually there is a deadline for the assessment. Once I put off an assignment until the deadline, I had to stay up all night to finish it. So, it is not wise to leave the work until the last minute. Later I learned to draw a circle of the date on my calendar if it is an assignment deadline or exam day.</p>', 'quenton', '2021-05-29 02:58:40', '2021-05-29 02:58:40'),
(4, 'My First Semester - Dipesh Pulami', '<p>I am an international student and I was very excited to get started when I got accepted into the university. After I got accepted, I arrived in Australia around 15 days before the semester began. I came to the university after a few days to know how to get started and what I need to do, as I was told to report to university after my arrival. Student Central was the place where I got to know about things I need to know. This is where I learned important things like:</p><ul><li>How to use my UON, myHub and Blackboard</li><li>I learned how to enroll in courses and select a suitable timetable for the courses</li></ul><p>After this I came to university to attend orientation where I got to get the feel of the university, it taught me on how the first semester is going to be like. For my first day, I arrived an hour earlier than the start time of my course to find the lecture hall. I used the maze map from the UON application to find the hall and like any other first day class, the professor gave a briefing on what the course is about and what we need to do. This is how my first semester of undergraduate degree in Information Technology began.</p><p>A couple of weeks of the first semester went in a blur as I was enjoying the experience of studying at an international university without realizing assessment of the courses were due. Suddenly the study load increased and it was almost hard for me to handle it. I did not realize most of the course assignments required a formation of a group in order to complete them. Then I got myself together and focused on assignments and formed a group to finish assignments on time. Assignments have their requirements and marking criteria and they require references which I did not have much knowledge of. I enquired about assignments with the course coordinator on what to do properly. Finally, I was able to finish my first set of assignments on time with correct procedure. Then came semester recess which is basically a two-week break, this was the time where I caught on the course studies where I was behind. In the break, I revisited the recorded lectures to overcome that. After the break, the courses continued as usual with quizzes and assignments, then the semester ended and exam time. Exams are very important as in most of the courses it is a mandatory thing to get a passing grade inorder to complete the course. Therefore, I revised all my courses’ lectures and study materials in order to prepare for the exam. After completing the exams ended this is how my first semester ended.</p><p>My suggestion for newly admitted students:</p><ul><li>Enroll in courses ahead of time so that you can choose course timetable suitable for you</li><li>AskUON and Student Central are important for students regarding any queries, they are there to help students</li><li>Get up to date with the university email that is Outlook so that you do not miss on the course announcements and update</li><li>In Information Technology degree, most of the assignments are group assignment, therefore try to form a group as soon as possible and do not forget put references where required</li></ul>', 'dipesh', '2021-05-29 02:59:26', '2021-05-29 02:59:26'),
(5, 'My First Semester - Dongyang Xie', '<p><strong>My first day</strong></p><p>On the first day of university, I, like most new students, used the interactive map on the UoN website to walk there. As I stood in advance and got off the bus near the student dormitory, I spent more money. It took nearly half an hour to arrive in the classroom. Fortunately, I started from home early, so I was not late for the first class.</p><p><strong>My first class</strong></p><p>My first class was also a lecture. Due to my early arrival, when I first arrived in the classroom, the last class in the classroom was not over yet, so I waited outside the classroom before entering after the end of the last class. My first course is divided into two parts: lecture and laboratory every week. In the first week, all students listen to the content of the course explained by the teacher. The laboratory starts from the second week. When participating in the laboratory, the four students are divided into groups. In the experiment class, the teacher will assign some classwork for group members to discuss, and then the group will feed back the results of the discussion to the teacher. This is a very interesting way of group interaction.</p><p><strong>Semester time</strong></p><p>After getting acquainted with the campus, I entered daily campus life. Several days a week, I need to take the school bus from downtown Newcastle to the Callaghan campus for classes. The journey will take me nearly 45 minutes. Since the courses in the first semester were relatively easy, I didn\'t encounter too much trouble in the process of learning. However, because English is not my native language, I occasionally encounter some troubles in communication and exchanges with the group, but fortunately, these problems have also been resolved through repeated communication. When encountering difficulties in the course, I usually take the initiative to communicate with teachers or other team members through emails and ask for their help. In most cases, they responded to my emails quickly. With their help, my assignment for the first semester was successfully completed.</p><p><strong>Exams</strong></p><p>For me, exams are very stressful. Due to time constraints, I often look up at the clock on the wall to confirm the time during the exam. In addition, the way to take the test is to put a piece of A4 size note paper into the test room, so I will try my best to write the key points in it before the test. This has led to most of my exam time looking for answers to questions on A4 paper. Fortunately, my preparation was quite adequate, and I passed the exams in the first semester smoothly.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'dongyang', '2021-05-30 11:28:16', '2021-05-30 11:28:16');

