(11, 'Accomodation', '<p class=\"center\"><iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/CdwSnCCRycc\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p><strong>In-campus living</strong></p><p><strong>Residences</strong></p><p>The university offers an unparalleled accommodation experience for university students.&nbsp;If you don\'t mind a higher fee and want to live close to the campus, residence in the campus is recommended.&nbsp;There are many advantages of living in campus: safe, near to the classrooms, fully equipped, what is rarer is that it is a great opportunity to make friends with different students.</p><p>Here is information about residences:</p><p><strong>Barahineban</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>Single, twin or double rooms available</li><li>Self-catered</li><li>En suite Bathroom</li><li>Private Kitchenette</li><li>General and Lifestyle areas&nbsp;</li><li>Air-conditioned</li><li>Mobility access</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/592623/Room-Inclusions-Barahineban.pdf\"><strong>https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/592623/Room-Inclusions-Barahineban.pdf</strong></a></p><p><strong>Edwards Hall</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>Private rooms&nbsp;</li><li>Shared facilities or ensuites</li><li>Fully-catered or self-catered</li><li>General, Lifestyle and Postgraduate areas</li><li>Heating, Swimming Pool and Dining Hall</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/592635/Room-Inclusions-Edwards-Hall.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/592635/Room-Inclusions-Edwards-Hall.pdf</a></p><p><strong>Evatt House</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>Shared and private living</li><li>Self-catered</li><li>General and Lifestyle areas</li><li>Air-conditioned</li><li>Large common room</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/592647/Room-Inclusions-Evatt-House.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/592647/Room-Inclusions-Evatt-House.pdf</a></p><p><strong>International House</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>Shared and private living</li><li>Self-catered</li><li>Heating&nbsp;</li><li>General and Lifestyle areas</li><li>Swimming pool</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/592661/Room-Inclusions-International-House.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/592661/Room-Inclusions-International-House.pdf</a></p><p><strong>North Residence</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>5/6 shared, one and two bedroom and studio apartments available</li><li>Self-catered</li><li>Lifestyle areas</li><li>Large communal kitchen</li><li>Mobility access</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/592666/Room-Inclusions-North,-South,-East-and-West-Residences.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/592666/Room-Inclusions-North,-South,-East-and-West-Residences.pdf</a></p><p><strong>South Residence</strong></p><p><strong>Key Features</strong></p><ul><li>5/6 shared, one and two bedroom and studio apartments available</li><li>Self-catered</li><li>General areas</li><li>Music room</li><li>Mobility access</li></ul><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/592666/Room-Inclusions-North,-South,-East-and-West-Residences.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/592666/Room-Inclusions-North,-South,-East-and-West-Residences.pdf</a></p><p><strong>Off-campus Living</strong></p><p>If you want a cheaper accommodation the university also provide information about off-campus living. You can find and filter relative options for a suitable room for you by going to this link:&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"https://offcampusaccommodation.newcastle.edu.au/\">https://offcampusaccommodation.newcastle.edu.au/</a></p><p><strong>Homestay</strong></p><p>If you are an international student and not adult, homestay might be suitable for you.&nbsp;</p><p>Homestay families provide international students with the opportunity to live in a family environment while studying at the university. Homestay families provide a homelike environment, while students can practice their language skills and form new friendships.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/international/before-you-leave/accommodation/homestay/what-to-expect\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/international/before-you-leave/accommodation/homestay/what-to-expect</a></p><p><strong>Homestay costs: </strong><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/international/before-you-leave/accommodation/homestay/costs-and-facilities\"><strong>https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/international/before-you-leave/accommodation/homestay/costs-and-facilities</strong></a></p><p><strong>References</strong></p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/student-living/where-can-i-live\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/student-living/where-can-i-live</a></p><p><a href=\"https://offcampusaccommodation.newcastle.edu.au/\">https://offcampusaccommodation.newcastle.edu.au/</a></p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/student-living/coming-from-overseas\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/study/student-living/coming-from-overseas</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'accomodation', 'blog', '2021-05-29 17:12:05', '2021-05-29 17:12:05'),
(2, 'Adverse Circumstances', '<p>In the course of study, some issues beyond your control might affect your ability to complete an assessment, take a test, or negatively affect your performance. We call these ‘Adverse Circumstances’.</p><p>Acceptable reasons for an Adverse Circumstances application are:</p><ul><li>health grounds</li><li>compassionate grounds</li><li>hardship</li><li>trauma</li><li>unavoidable commitments</li></ul><p>Adverse Circumstances do not include:</p><ul><li>misreading the Course Outline or examination timetable.</li><li>usual work commitments.</li><li>travel plans.</li><li>being unaware of the assumed knowledge requirements for your course</li></ul><p>Wisely use of ‘Adverse Circumstances’ is allowed, helps you easier to deal with extra issues.</p><p>You must tell the University about your adverse circumstances in advance of your assessment being due and prior to your exam.</p><p>Check Adverse Circumstances Affecting Assessment Items Procedure to learn how to apply.</p><p><a href=\"https://policies.newcastle.edu.au/document/view-current.php?id=236\">https://policies.newcastle.edu.au/document/view-current.php?id=236</a></p><p>Check Adverse Circumstances Affecting Assessment Items Policy to ensure your reasons will be considered valid.</p><p><a href=\"https://policies.newcastle.edu.au/document/view-current.php?id=235\">https://policies.newcastle.edu.au/document/view-current.php?id=235</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'adverse-circumstances', 'blog', '2021-05-29 17:16:43', '2021-05-29 17:16:43'),
(3, 'Academics', '<p><strong>Grading System</strong></p><p>Academic performance is usually graded at the end of each term and the final assessment can include assignment and tutorial work, examinations and practical work. The grading scale used at the University is as follows:</p><p><strong>Grading Scale</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>HD</td><td>&nbsp;85 - 100</td><td>High Distinction</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>&nbsp;75 - 84</td><td>Distinction</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>&nbsp;65 - 74</td><td>Credit</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>&nbsp;50 - 64</td><td>Pass</td></tr><tr><td>UP</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>You have been awarded an Ungraded Pass. There are no marks associated with this result and you have met the level requirements to pass the course.</td></tr><tr><td>FF</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>Fail</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Administrative Codes</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;I</td><td><p><strong>Incomplete</strong>. Not all the information is available to calculate a mark at this stage. Reasons for this may be that you have still to provide an assessment requirement or that the Lecturer has yet to complete the marking. If you are unsure about the reasons for this mark you should contact the school office.</p><p><strong>\"I\" results are automatically&nbsp;converted to \"FF\" after 90 days.</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;S</td><td><strong>Special Consideration</strong>. The result is pending the outcome of an application for Special Circumstances. \"S\" results are&nbsp;automatically converted to \"FF\" after 180 days if the result is not amended.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;NA</td><td><strong>Grade not applicable</strong></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;-</td><td><strong>Grade or score not applicable</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>GPA</strong></p><p>Your grade point average (GPA) is the average result of all your grades and is calculated on a 7-point grading scale. 7 being the highest (HD), and 0 is the lowest (fail).</p><p>Identify what grade you received for each course:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grades</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td><td><strong>Value</strong></td></tr><tr><td>HD</td><td>High Distinction</td><td>7</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Distinction</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>Credit</td><td>5</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>Pass</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>UP</td><td>Ungraded pass</td><td>4*</td></tr><tr><td>F</td><td>Fail</td><td>0</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>*Ungraded passes (UP) are not usually included in the calculation of a GPA, for exceptions see the&nbsp;</i><a href=\"https://policies.newcastle.edu.au/document/view-current.php?id=157\"><i>GPA Calculation Guideline</i></a><i>.</i></p><p><strong>Reference</strong></p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/study-essentials/assessment-and-exams/results/gpa-calculator\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/study-essentials/assessment-and-exams/results/gpa-calculator</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'academics', 'blog', '2021-05-29 17:26:15', '2021-05-29 17:26:15'),
(4, 'Examination', '<p><strong>Exam information</strong></p><p>Exams are a stressful time for all students, and here we will explain how they usually ‘go’ and what you should normally have before exams and what you should normally know before it.</p><p><strong>What you should know</strong></p><p>Unfortunately, you will have to study for each exam, the power of studying an exam can pitch you up for a very high mark in the exam which is very important for future ventures.</p><p>Going throughout the semester, for a particular course, you will know your weak points inside the course. We advise that you study these first, this will strengthen these weak points and you will not struggle with these in the exam. These always may take the most time, so you should start off with these!</p><p>Different exams have different permissions, so for most engineering exams you will allowed a ‘reference sheet’ or otherwise known as a ‘cheat sheet’ which you can put any information on that sheet that you can reference from within the exam. This sheet is one A4 piece of paper which can be written on both sides.</p><p>Also, exams are open book, but you should not bring every book that you have relating to the course, as this can make you run out of time in the exam.</p><p><strong>How an exam plans out</strong></p><p>We shall talk about when you go in for an exam, as this is the catalyst for most students. (I promise you this is okay! Every is going to be anxious, stressed and all kinds of things. Everyone is feeling the pressure as much as you!)</p><p>Once you reach a theatre or anything similar, you will be seated, you may need to find your seat number before hand, (unless its an online exam) and you will be read out instructions on what you can have out (aka calculator, pencil, pens). During this time you will have to be completely silent, as these are exam rules.</p><p>Once you get your paper, the exam supervisors will write a reading commencement time, and during this time you can look through your exam paper and go through what you are being assessed against.&nbsp;</p><p>Use this time wisely! You should flip through all the pages first, reading through each question. Then you can decide what questions you can answer right away and figure out what would be the most time efficient! (for example, if you feel more comfortable doing the longer parts of the exam first, you should, and then come back to the shorter stuff later. In these exams you should always aim for the most marks!)</p><p>Time management within an exam is very important, and this is why we say if you feel more comfortable doing something else first, rather doing the paper in order, is because the stuff you feel more accustomed to doing, means you will most likely do it faster then something you don’t have in your head as of that moment.</p><p>Then once the reading time is done the exam supervisors will allow you to start the exam, so making a little plan during the reading time is super good to do. But you do not need to do this every time.</p><p><strong>Different type of exams</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Multiple exams can span into different area of ways being done, such as:</p><ul><li>Online exams</li><li>Mid-term exams</li><li>In-class exams</li><li>Practical exam</li><li>Final exam</li></ul><p><strong>Online Exams</strong></p><p>The exams that are online, are done through blackboard. These exams are the close to the same as an in-class exam, but these are done in the comfort of home on your computer, these exams can be at a set time, or over a span of time which must be done between those times. For example</p><p>A set time would be “Exam starts are 3:00pm and ends at 5:00pm” This means if you do not get on and do the exam in those times you cannot participate and will get a 0. (Personally would get on nearly 10 minutes early to check for emails and be ready for the entire time.</p><p>A spanned time would be “Exam can be started at 10:00am, and will end at 7:00pm. Only 2 hours of time permitted”. This means that the exam can be started between 10am-7pm but only 2 hours of time will be given once you press start on the exam, so be ready for it before pressing start! Also if you start it less to 2 hours before 7pm (i.e 6:30pm). You will only be given the time before the exam finished. (So if you start at 6:30pm you would only have 30 minutes to complete an exam that is supposed to take 2 hours).</p><p><strong>Mid-term Exams</strong></p><p>Mid-term exams are an exam that is usually done within your lecture time, which will cover the information that you have covered from the weeks before. (i.e. These happen around week 6, so everything before this will be covered and you should know).</p><p><strong>In-class Exams</strong></p><p>These exams will most likely feel like high-school tests, these are a check-up if you are keeping up with the content within the course. These are assessable so looking a couple days before over the content that will be covered in the exam should always be looked at.</p><p><strong>Practical Exam</strong></p><p>Practical exams are to demonstrate if you understand the practical aspect of the course, this is mainly done within coding course, for example within the course INFT2012, the paper you receive is instructions on what must be done in a set amount of time.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Final Exam</strong></p><p>Final exams are the biggest stress for most students, it is similar to in-class and mid-term exams, but just means a lot more.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'examination', 'blog', '2021-05-29 17:28:48', '2021-05-29 17:28:48'),
(5, 'Lectures & Workshops', '<p>When becoming accustomed getting to, and around university, the next thing to figure out is how Lectures and Workshops (Also called tutorial and Labs).</p><p>On this page we will explain on how a normal lecture and Workshop will usually go. This is to help students understand when it is the right time to show up, leave or ask questions.</p><p>Be sure you know where you’re going to your class, check for the apps you need for getting around campus <a href=\"getting-around-campus\">here</a>.</p><p>Some details on what you should have before showing up to a lecture or workshop.</p><ul><li>Pen and Paper</li><li>Laptop (If you don’t have one can use Pen and Paper as an alternative)</li><li>Backpack (To put your stuff in)</li><li>Student Card</li></ul><p>Once you have all your stuff and have revised where you need to for your first lecture or workshop, we will explain on how they usually plan out.</p><p><strong>What to do before lectures / workshops</strong></p><p>Look over the supplied lecture/workshop slides on blackboard, this will give you an idea of what they are going to be going over.</p><p><strong>Why do this?</strong></p><p>Getting a head start on the topic you are talking about is fantastic start to any discussion about it, this opens questions on some areas that you don’t fully understand.</p><ul><li>Knowledgeable of the topic, and being able to fully understand the weekly topic</li><li>Helpful for assessments</li><li>Knowing what to reference for exams notes&nbsp;</li></ul><p>There are two forms of lectures/workshops nowadays, being:</p><ul><li>Online</li><li>Face to face</li></ul><p><strong>Online Lectures</strong></p><p>There are two ways of course coordinators doing online lectures:</p><ul><li>Zoom</li><li>Blackboard Collaborate</li></ul><p><strong>Zoom</strong></p><p>Zoom is the mainly used application which will have to be downloaded on your local device, this can be downloaded on Windows, Mac, iOS and Android. If you are not able to use one of those, the campus will have computers that you can use to attend.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Blackboard Collaborate</strong></p><p>Blackboard Collaborate is sometimes used for Lectures and/or workshops. This can be accessed via blackboard on Mac or Windows. If you are not able to use one of those, the campus will have computers that you can use to attend.</p><p><strong>Face to face Lectures</strong></p><p>These lectures are the mainly used ones, the online alternatives are used if the university can not be attended. These will involve you going to the lecture room on campus, and will be watching the slides that you have looked over, and discussing/learn the topic for the week.</p><p>Link ref: <a href=\"https://images.app.goo.gl/S8pG2oAC1AsL7ztK7\">https://images.app.goo.gl/S8pG2oAC1AsL7ztK7</a></p><p>Lectures will normally have a lecturer out the front that talk about the slides that will be on a big screen displaying to all students, they will talk about the slides, and that will be the topic/topics you will be learning for the week. These are very beneficial to go to because these will help you in assessments and exams.</p><p>Lectures go for around 1-2 Hours long, sometimes with a 5 minutes break in between the hours on a 2 hour lecture.</p><p>Lectures start 5 minutes are the hour and finish 5 minutes before the hour. So what this means is that if there was a lecture on at 1pm and it went to 3pm, it would technically start at 1:05pm and finish at 2:55pm. But this does not mean you should leave it to the last minute, this buffer is only to allow students time for walking across campus.</p><p>Getting you lectures 5 minutes early should be the aim.</p><p><strong>Workshops</strong></p><p>These are much similar to high school classes, you will be going over that was learnt from the lecture, and be applying it to some similar work to help understand the topic. This is a much more lax area, where you will be able to communicate with other students and a teacher which may be the lecturer.&nbsp;</p><p>A couple tips would be:</p><p>Don’t be shy, ask questions</p><p>If you don’t understand something, you should ask a questions, even if it sound silly it will help yourself in the long run.</p><p>Try to finish the work</p><p>Though it isn’t required, finishing the work means that you most likely understand the content for the week.</p><p>These workshops sometimes happen in computer labs (especially for students doing a course in computing) and most students in there will be in the same situation as you, all learning the same thing so don’t be scared!</p><p>These also can be online, nearly identical to online lectures.</p><p>The teachers are very friendly and are always there to help you with all problems about the work for the week, and will help you understand it if you are stuck.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'lectures-workshops', 'blog', '2021-05-29 17:49:17', '2021-05-29 17:49:17'),
(6, 'Zoom', '<p>Zoom is a video conferencing software that helps to provide communications and distance education. Recently, Zoom has gained popularity and has become an integral part of daily lives due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The University of Newcastle has used Zoom to provide education for student that cannot make it to the university through Zoom. Furthermore, the university uses Zoom to provide services like counselling, discussions and communication for students who are at home. Therefore, it is important to learn about Zoom. You can download Zoom for computers and mobiles at <a href=\"https://zoom.us/download\">here.</a></p><p>Following is the video on how to use Zoom:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"center\"><iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/QOUwumKCW7M\"\r\n                    title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\"\r\n                    allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\r\n                    allowfullscreen>\r\n                </iframe>\r\n</p>', 'zoom', 'blog', '2021-05-30 15:49:30', '2021-05-30 15:49:30'),
(7, 'BlackBoard', '<p>Blackboard learn is an application used by the University of Newcastle for virtual learning. Blackboard is a learning management system that is used for online teaching, discussion and knowledge sharing. Students can keep track of their courses through Blackboard. It is one of the most important tools where lecturers and student make connection on their course studies. All the resources and criteria for a course is accessible through this system. Assignments, examination, course information and a course contacts can be found in Blackboard.It displays all the courses taken by the student in one easy accessible place. Student have to upload their assignments and participate on quizzes from Blackboard unless otherwise advised by the course coordinator. You can access Blackboard by using this <a href=\"https://uonline.newcastle.edu.au/\">link</a>. &nbsp;</p><p>You learn to use Blackboard through this video:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"center\"><iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/MzLV7x3nuSc\"\r\n                    title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\"\r\n                    allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\r\n                    allowfullscreen>\r\n                </iframe></p>', 'blackboard', 'blog', '2021-05-30 15:59:42', '2021-05-30 15:59:42'),
(8, 'myUON', '<p>myUON is the Swiss army knife web application for students at the University of Newcastle. Students have all the tools necessary in one place like: Blackboard, Exams, timetable, personal details and so on. By entering correct student credentials student can access the website and view their activity in the university. Therefore, learning how to use it is must. You can access myUON using this <a href=\"https://myuon.newcastle.edu.au/\">link</a>.</p><p>Following is the video on how to use myUON:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"centre\"><iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/h9dNP81VEFQ\"\r\n                    title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\"\r\n                    allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\r\n                    allowfullscreen>\r\n                </iframe></p>', 'myuon', 'blog', '2021-05-30 16:11:38', '2021-05-30 16:11:38'),
(9, 'Navigating the University', '<p><strong>MazeMap</strong></p><p>As a student who has passed the first year, I know one of the troubles faced by first year students is that the university is a completely unfamiliar environment to them. Usually, it takes you several weeks to become familiar with various buildings and facilities. But with the help of MazeMap this process could be easier. MazeMap is a useful app especially for first year students, it provides detailed maps of the University’s campuses, including the location of lecture theaters, tutorial rooms, computer labs and toilets. It also shows you the nearest bus stops, university services, sporting venues, shops, food outlets, coffee, vending machines, water bubblers and free microwaves! Use it to show you both where your next class is and how best to get there. I used this app to show where my next class is and how best to get there, it saved me lots of time.</p><p><a href=\"https://use.mazemap.com/#v=1\">https://use.mazemap.com/#v=1</a></p><p><strong>Shuttle bus services</strong></p><p>It is common to stay late in the collage, but do not need to worry about how to get back home.&nbsp;The University has free shuttle services for students and staff to get you to and from – or around – campus.</p><p>You could track the Campus Shuttle in real time with the myUON&nbsp;app.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/support/it/student-systems/mobile-apps\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/support/it/student-systems/mobile-apps</a></p><p><strong>Bike hubs</strong></p><p>The hubs are undercover, secure bike storage spaces with end of trip facilities and bike repair equipment.</p><p><strong>Parking</strong></p><p>If you choose driving to the collage, here are some information that may help you:</p><p><strong>Parking permits</strong></p><p>Students can purchase either an annual or six month permit. Purchasing a parking permit does not guarantee you a parking bay, but it does mean you don’t need to find change or stop and pay at a ticket machine.</p><p><strong>Ticketed parking</strong></p><p>Coin and credit card operated ticket machines are located throughout the campus if you do not wish to purchase a parking permit. The 2020 daily rate for parking is $4.60. Please note that the machines do not give change.</p><p><strong>Accessible parking</strong></p><p>Any person who has been granted an NSW or inter-state Mobility Parking Scheme permit, including an Australian Disability Permit, is able to park in Disabled, Staff and General bays free of charge. Your valid parking scheme permits must be clearly displayed on the passenger side of your front windscreen. Please note that RTA Mobility Parking Scheme conditions apply.</p><p>If you require closer parking due to a temporary medical condition, you can apply for a university disability access permit by contacting the AccessAbility team</p><p><strong>Motorcycle parking</strong></p><p>Motorcycle parking on Callaghan and Ourimbah campuses is free, and no permit is required. Motorcycles must be parked in a designated motorcycle parking bay only. Motorcycles located in bays other than the designated areas may be subject to a fine.</p><p><strong>Public Transport</strong></p><p><strong>Bus</strong></p><p>There are local bus stops outside:</p><ul><li>Design Building and the Mathematics Building on campus</li><li>University Drive just outside campus.</li></ul><p><strong>Train</strong></p><p>Warabrook Station is located on the edge of the Callaghan campus. You can choose to walk from the station or catch the Safety and Security shuttle that has a stop right outside.</p><p><strong>Reference</strong></p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/uni-life/campus/getting-to-campus/callaghan\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/current-students/uni-life/campus/getting-to-campus/callaghan</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'navigation', 'blog', '2021-05-30 16:35:52', '2021-05-30 16:35:52'),
(1, 'Welcome', '<p>Congratulations on making it into the University of Newcastle! Now there is a bit of knowledge you should have before entering your first week of university.</p><p>Getting into university is the first step, and the next couple of steps is getting accustomed to university and university life. As by no surprise university is full of opportunity and enjoyment when knowing everything that is going on. Which is why this guide has come to help you.&nbsp;</p><p>University is full of opportunity and foundations to get you a flying start in your working career, and here is the place where you can become ready for your first day at the University of Newcastle.&nbsp;</p><p>Some things to start you off with university is getting there! For Callaghan there are many places you can you start, such as trains, driving, uber, rideshare, walking and many more.</p><p>Other activities such as events, your scheduled lectures, tutorials, labs, and other day to day things you will be doing on campus.</p><p>Lectures and tutorials work hand in hand. You will attend lectures that you will find on your blackboard <a href=\"https://uonline.newcastle.edu.au/\">website</a>. Which you will get taught about content in the lecture, and then delve into it in a simpler basis and maybe more hands-on approach to help understand the content.</p><p>Activities range from multiple things such as, joining a club, sporting and/or charity days, these are advertised around the university for you to do.</p><p>By going through this website will guide you through university and everything you need to know. So follow on while we help you out from a student point of view on how university is going to feel.&nbsp;</p><p>Getting around Campus could one of the first challenge you may come across, but this guide will help you on your way to lectures and other great places on the campus!</p><p>The list of “must have” things before coming to University for getting around are:</p><p>They are as follows:</p><ul><li>App “Lost On Campus”</li><li>App “Blackboard”</li><li>App “myUON”</li></ul><p><strong>Lost on Campus</strong></p><p>The Lost on Campus application provides a map and direction on where you need to go for your classes and other amenities around campus, which may include food, toilet, etc.</p><p>This application is available on iOS and Android.</p><p>This is the main application that will be used for getting around university.&nbsp; This will get you to the room you need to go to. But in some areas around university, it doesn’t have, so you will have pin point that room yourself, but it should show you the way to a building. For example, here:</p><p>Say you needed to go to the ES building, not for exactly ES-204, but for ES-241 for example, it would get you most of the way there. Then once you are inside the building there are multiple ways on finding the correct room.</p><p>There are maps on each floor on the walls as entering each floor, this will help you around the floor and where your actual room is. Or you could ask someone.</p><p>If you are unable to get the app, there are other ways to figure out where to go. Here is an interactive map that you can pull up on your phone.</p><p>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/campus-life/newcastle/callaghan/map\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/campus-life/newcastle/callaghan/map</a></p><p>If unable to use your phone here is a PDF of the map</p><p><a href=\"https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/40842/Callaghan-Campus-Map-20180507.pdf\">https://www.newcastle.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/40842/Callaghan-Campus-Map-20180507.pdf</a></p><p><strong>Blackboard App</strong></p><p>Now the next two applications coming up won’t exactly ‘help’ you getting around campus, but update you for where you need to go on campus.</p><p>This app is available on iOS and Android.</p><p>The blackboard application lets you be able to look at what will be on the lecture slides (most of the time, some course coordinators don’t upload lecture slides until the actual lecture starts). And be able to get updates on room location if it was to move. This doesn’t happen very often at all.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>More on blackboard </strong><a href=\"/post/blackboard\"><strong>here</strong></a></p><p><strong>MyUON App</strong></p><p>The myUON Application has a wide arrange of very useful information for getting around university, ranging from your timetable which has the time and the room you are meant to be attending, and also being able to visit blackboard from this application also.</p><p>(Note: The blackboard app is still more useful as it is much easier to use)</p><p>This is the application view when logging in. As you can see most information can be accessed from this, but mainly for what we are talking about, the getting around tab is what we will look at.</p><p>(This is also accessible from your myUON webpage on computers)</p><p>Campus maps, shuttles (if needing to go into the city for classes) and other very useful information is displayed within this app and can be used to get around university.</p><p>This page is mainly focused towards the Callaghan campus, but the application works with other campus’ so it can be used in those locations also.</p><p>Shuttles are used to get around university safely and quickly. They are on for all hours of the day, ranging from 7am to around 12 midnight.&nbsp; So, if needed be used, you can access it here.</p><p><strong>More information on travel </strong><a href=\"/post/navigation\"><strong>here</strong></a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'welcome', 'blog', '2021-05-28 16:50:48', '2021-05-28 16:50:48');

